<HEADLINE>
<P>
BALZER ON WINE: TIME FOR WINE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Robert Lawrence Balzer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINE HAS ALWAYS BEEN a hard sell in the United States because it has not been 
understood as a natural companion for food -- part of a healthful regimen. The 
autumn harvest of 1990 arrived under threatening clouds of "sin tax" ballot 
measures and federal legislation threatening the very existence of grape 
growing and winemaking in the state. Yet, it is always time for wine. 
</P>
<P>
"We've got to put the glass or bottle of wine on the table, right there with 
the hamburgers, pizzas and tacos," says Sheldon (Hack) Wilson, owner /vintner 
of Chimney Rock in the Napa Valley. "What we need," he says, "is a definition 
that comes as easy as Coke's 'Pause that refreshes,' which tells the story 
without any insinuating stuffy rigmarole." 
</P>
<P>
There was a challenge. We left it with his suggestion: "It's always time for 
wine . . . the civilized refreshment." 
</P>
<P>
While I was in the Napa Valley, I also stopped at Monticello Cellars, where the 
Napa Valley Vintners Assn. was having its annual Crush Celebration. Guest 
harvesters from all over came to pick grapes and assist in the crush and 
fermentation (while wearing rubber boots), alongside all the regulars. There 
were tales to tell and good laughs. 
</P>
<P>
One week later, I flew to Switzerland to observe the harvest in the Canton of 
Vaud, which fronts Lac Leman of Geneva, home of the vine since Roman times. The 
harvest was in full swing. As in the Napa Valley, laughter, songs and shouts of 
merriment were everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
Swiss wine growers promote the ubiquitous golden Chasselas grape as having a 
very subtle flavor . . . and taking character from the different soils in which 
it is grown. True. I tasted dozens of wines of Chasselas origins from the 
separate appellations. None were the same. Some were earth-earthy, some had 
subtle aromas, and others defied description. But all were delicate, with an 
appetizing dryness. 
</P>
<P>
In Switzerland, as in other parts of Europe, wine is part of the food regimen 
and is consumed regularly. 
</P>
<P>
Back in America, with Thanksgiving days away, it's almost redundant to say, 
"It's time for wine!" But it is time, now, at Thanksgiving and whenever. "It's 
always time for wine . . . the civilized refreshment." Robert Lawrence Balzer 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
