<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA111890-0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 309792 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 18, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Opinion; Part M; Page 6; Column 4; Letters Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
181 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
PAYING TAXES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What kind of people are willing to sacrifice their daughters and sons but 
refuse to sacrifice their money? 
</P>
<P>
The only concrete way in which most of us can show our patriotism is to pay our 
taxes. 
</P>
<P>
Flying the flag and singing "God Bless America" are symbolic ways of showing 
our gratitude for what our country has given us. But we have schools and 
freeways and hospitals to use because someone paid for them -- with taxes. 
</P>
<P>
Incredibly, many so-called patriotic Americans are contemptuous of men and 
women who object to sacrificing their lives in pursuit of a questionable 
foreign policy. These same "patriots" see nothing inconsistent in voting 
against anyone who suggests that paying taxes is a necessary part of good 
citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
The only war most "conservative" patriots ever opposed was the "War on 
Poverty." They opposed it because it attempted to take some of their money and 
use it to help other Americans. Apparently, it's OK to send our youth away to 
help defend other governments, but it's not OK to send our money to help our 
own! 
</P>
<P>
ROBERT C. VON BARGEN 
</P>
<P>
Toluca Lake 
</P>
</TEXT>
