Europe and the Middle East with a stop in Prague, Czechoslovakia, the first 
visit there by a U.S. president. In a speech to a huge crowd in the city's 
Wenceslas Square, he delivered a message aimed largely to Americans at home: 
"The freedom of people everywhere remains under threat" from the aggression of 
Iraq. Before the speech, he addressed the Czechoslovak Parliament. Right, 
Czechoslovak leader Vaclav Havel and Bush review honor guard at the airport 
