<HEADLINE>
<P>
A SENSITIVE ARTICLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nora Zamichow's recent article ("In a Second, His Life Changed for the Worse," 
Nov. 12) on head injury survivor John Joseph Luz and his family was 
outstanding. As the parent of a daughter who sustained a traumatic head injury 
at age 16, and as president of the San Diego Head Injury Foundation, I read 
avidly any news coverage given this topic. 
</P>
<P>
Ms. Zamichow's work was exceptional in that she captured the pain, frustration 
and "torment," as Mr. Luz so thoughtfully put it, of life after head injury, 
with all its attendant cognitive and physical impairments. It was a most 
sensitive article. 
</P>
<P>
Head injury survivors and their family members need a great deal of support 
from loved ones and friends, and from self-help organizations such as ours. 
</P>
<P>
The San Diego Head Injury Foundation offers a monthly newsletter, educational 
meetings, support groups and an informational telephone line: (619) 569-5699. 
We invite your readers with questions to call. 
</P>
<P>
PATRICIA MARSHALL 
</P>
<P>
President 
</P>
<P>
San Diego Head Injury Foundation 
</P>
